<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Country Land and Business Association </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 1: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you think the Government should introduce a biodiversity offsetting system in England? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Yes, very much so. We have been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">making the case for market based solutions, to environmental problems, including offsetting, since 2009 and the publication of our report “Private Solutions to Public Problems”.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">In an age of austerity, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">we need to be looking at new ways to pay </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">for biodivers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ity. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Even if the budget for the new CAP is only marginally less than the current one, it is unlikely that there will be sufficient public funds to do meet all of society’s aspirations in the long term.  One of the most straightforward ways of levering in m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ore funding is through ecosystems markets by which those who benefit from the provision of environmental  services contribute to the costs; particularly developers being required to provide offsets to replace </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the loss of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">biodiversity as a condition of obta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ining planning permission. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Similarly, there is of course the requirement for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provision of compensatory habitat under the Habitats Directive. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, we would emphasise that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">these arrangements will only find favour with landowners if they enter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to them </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">voluntarily. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Any system based on or involving the comp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ulsory acquisition of land will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be unacceptable to the vast majority of landowners. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As such we see </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">offsetting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as being primarily a commercial matter with the landowner deciding that he wishes to dedicate his land for conservation purposes so long as the price is right. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 2: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">o you think the Government’s objectives for the system and the characteristics the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic"> Government thinks a system would display are right? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Although we do not claim to speak for the sort of developers likely to be obliged to provide offsets, we think that anything that brings certainty to the planning system by enabling developers to predi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ct from the outset what is expected of them will result in a faster </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">and almost certainly cheaper </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">system. Nevertheless, the system must not have the effect of making much needed small scale developments in the countryside unviable. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We strongly believe tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">t offsetting will bring net benefits for biodiversity. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We agree with the proposed characteristics. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 3: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you think it is appropriate to base an offsetting system on the pilot metric? If not is there an alternative metric that should be used? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">e support the aspiration that the metric needs to be both simple and able to cope with a range of habitat types.  We are not aware of any other metric which better achieves this.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 4: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">If you think the pilot metric is the right basis for an offsetti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">ng system: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">(a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Are there </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">any other factors which should be considered when quantifying biodiversity loss and gain?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We think the factors themselves are correct, but some subdivision may be appropriate.  For example, it would be useful to include a specific reference to “age” under distinctiveness. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">(b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Are the weights given to the different factors appropriate?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Yes </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">(c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Are there any other changes you think should be taken into account? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We are not aware of any. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">(Please also refer to questions under section 6) </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 5: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you think offsetting assessment should be used when preparing a planning application for a pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">oject? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Yes, subject to considerations such as thresholds.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Ques</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">tion 6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">o you agree that it should be the responsibility of planning authorities to ensure the mitigation hierarchy is observed and decide what offset is required to compensate for any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">residual loss</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">?  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">If not, why, and how do you think offsetting should be approached in the planning system? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We do think it should be the responsibility of the planning authority.  But we are very conscious of the need to avoid placing additional burdens on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> developers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The amount of information a developer is obliged to supply in support of an application is already excessive. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">As such we suggest a short statement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, for consideration by the planning authority, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">setting out how he has complied with the hierarchy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> should be sufficient. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">If a developer is required to spend time and money in obtaining consultants reports it will defeat one of the main objectives of offsetting. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Question 7: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you think biodiversity offsetting should have a role in all development con</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">sent regimes?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Yes. We see no reason to differentiate between the various terrestrial development consent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">regimes. We would support the introduction of an offsetting obligation for HS2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">other</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> large infrastructure projects.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 8: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you think developers should be able to choose whether to use offsetting? If so what steps could Government take to encourage developers to use offsetting? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Although instinctively we would prefer a voluntary approach we suspect, to be viable, the system will need to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">be mandatory</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, subject to thresholds, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">both in terms of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">assessment and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">the requirement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">to offset</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.  Unless the system is mandatory we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">doubt we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ll be able to ensure the level of investor confidence required to produce the number of offset sites required. Landowners will not think it worth their while looking into offsetting if there are only a few random developers looking for offsets. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">If</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic"> you think developers should be required to use offsetting do you think this requirement should only apply above a threshold based on the size of the development? What level should the threshold be? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Yes.  We support the use of thresholds rather than</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> requirements to assess the significance of the developments impact. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">From our experiences with the concept</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">s use under the Habitats Regulations and the EIA Directive, s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ignificance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">difficult to measure and invariably requires the use of consultants.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We suggest that the threshold should be based on the viability of the development.  It should certainly not be so low as to discourage the small scale developments in rural villages or settlements tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">t are required to deal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> with the lack</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> of housing in the c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ountryside.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> On this basis we believe it should be at least 10 units. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">There is no discussion in the consultation paper about what the thresholds would be for other developments, such as road building. We suggest there should be no thresholds in such cases</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 10</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you think there should be constraints on where offsets can be located? If so what constraints do you think should be put in place? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The location of offsets is a difficult issue. We can see merits in consolidating the offsets resulting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from a number of small developments in one location to create something bigger and better, or to fill in the gaps between protected sites as per the Lawton report.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Moreover, if </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there is a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> requirement that the offset must be local to the development, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re may be a difficulty with the number of potential offset providers available. In some localities with only a small number of landowners, those landowners could charge “ransom values” to provide the requisite offsets. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Nevertheless, we understand the con</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cerns that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">such an approach may result in the offset being some distance from the related development and local people suffering the possible detrimental impact of the development without obtaining the benefit of the offset.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As such whilst the offset do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es not have to be next to the development it should not be too far away</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a compromise between these various factors we suggest that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the very least</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> development and the offset </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should be in the same county, although we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">appreciate that this is not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> an ideal situation. If you develop on the northern border of a county then your perfect offsetting site may be a mile away across the boundary and you may be searching for a suitable site 30 miles away further south to stay with the same county</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It may be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that localities based on other than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">administrative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">boundaries could also be used, such as water catchments.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 11:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">o you have any comments on the analysis set out in the impact assessment? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 12: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you have evidence that would help refine the Government’s analysis of the costs and benefits of the options considered in this paper? In particular, evidence relating to: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">(a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">The amount of compensation already occurring where there is residual biodiversity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic"> loss which cannot be avoided or adequately mitigated </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">(b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">The method for estimating costs and their magnitude </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">(c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">The method for estimating benefits and savings and their magnitude </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt; text-indent:-35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">(d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">How to capture the wider social and environmental benefits of maintaining England’s stock of biodiversity and delivering a coherent ecological network </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">(e)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Likely take up of offsetting under a permissive approach </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 13: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you think offsetting should b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">e a single consistent national system without scope for local variation? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Yes, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">a single consistent national system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> is essential.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">To </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">work offsetting will require a nationwide market and that in turn requires one nationwide system.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">There are already a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">mass of local schemes out there</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, each</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">their own exponents. It will make developers and landowners lives difficult if everyone has to get their minds around different schem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">es in every part of the country.</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 14: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you agree with the proposed e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">xceptions to the routine use of biodiversity offsetting? If not, why not? If you suggest additional restriction, why are they needed? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Yes. We agree with the analysis in the Consultation paper. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">hich</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">habitats do you think should be considered irreplaceable? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">No.  The importance of an irreplaceable habitat should be taken into account through the planning system and the mitigation hierarchy.  The question is the multiplier for destroying such habitats.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We suggest particular attention needs to be given to connectivity and the possibility that a habitat may have an added value because of its location. For example the value of a particular site may not be high in itself, but it may have considerable sign</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ificance as part of a corridor. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 16: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you think offsetting should in principle be applied to protected species? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Yes.  We do, although we accept the complexity of the issue.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The extent to which the suspected or possible presence of, in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">particular bats, newts and dormice can frustrate or delay farm diversification projects such as barn conversions is a significant concern, particularly since under resourced planning departmen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ts are increasingly inclined to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> err on the side of caution. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 17</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">as the Government identified the right constraints and features that need to be addressed when applying offsetting to protected species? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We believe so.  They certainly reflect the complexity of the legal regime. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 18</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">o you agree </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">that great crested newts should be the first area of focus? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We would prefer it to be bats, but would not object to great crested newts. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 19</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">o you have any comments on the Government’s thinking on how to apply offsetting to great crested newts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We support it, and suggest it provides a suitable model for other species. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">hould offsetting be considered for any other species in the near future taking account of the constraints on species offsetting? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Yes. Bats and dormice. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 21: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you think conservation covenants should be put in place as part of an offsetting system? If they are required, who do you think should be responsible for agreeing conservation covenants? If not, how else do you think offsets could be secure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">d for the long-term? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We accept the limitations of both freehold and leasehold covenants in th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is context.  However we have been closely engaged with the Law Commission’s work in this area and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">suspect that what the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">describes as “workarounds” may have grea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ter potential than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">they believe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Nevertheless we accept the desirability of creating new legal mechanisms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and a simple way of avoiding the problems with conventional covenants. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 22</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">o you think management agreements should be put in place as part of an offsetting system? If they are required, who do you think should be responsible for agreeing management agreements? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In our view a management plan setting out the parties aspirations f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or the land, rather like the Views about Management statement required for SSSIs, would be more useful than an agreement.  We suspect any agreement would simply be a parallel document to the conservation covenant. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If management plans were to be introduced</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> maintain they should be a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">matter for negotiation between the parties.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> There are plenty of priva</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">te organisations, such as FWAG </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which think would be capable of acting as facilitators. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 23</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">o you think an offset register should be put in plac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">e as part of an offsetting system? If so, who do you think should be responsible for maintaining an offset register? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">do not see any need for any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">central recording of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">offsets</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we would not object to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that responsible bodies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">being encouraged </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">publish information voluntarily, with the agreement of the relevant landowner.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">4:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">How long should offsets be secured for? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are pleased the question has been asked. The presumption that offsets should be secured in perpetuity has been a parti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cular cause for concern.  We think it fundamentally wrong to dictate the use of a particular piece of land for ever. We suggest that few people would think that a land use determined in 1813 still had any great relevance, and similarly that in 2213, few wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ll think a use set now was still appropriate. Moreover, we suspect that many landowners will see little that is attractive about </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dedicating land in perpetuity. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">They might as well sell it. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As such, we suggest that the default position should be something </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">less than perpetu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ity –</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">66</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> years may be a more reasonable timescale. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In any event a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">certain amount of flex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ibility in the management plan will be required so that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">so that it can adapt in the l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ight of changing circumstances.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 25</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">re there any long-term factors, besides climate change, that should be taken into account when securing offsets? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Statutory designations allow for revocations or modifications in the light of changing circumstances.  We see no reason why conservation cove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nants should be any different.  Climate change, in particular  will result in many changes to the uses to which particular land can be put and will also impact on the location o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f suitable habitats for certain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">species, as such we should be encouraging the d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">evelopment of flexible structures. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Attention should also be given to other sources of biodiversity funding. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In particular, with the increasing probability that the CAP budget</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will be significantly reduced </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">over the coming years, the need to secure other s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ources of funding becomes all the greater. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 26: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Do you think biodiversity offsetting should be” backdated” so it can apply in relation to any planning applications under consideration at the point it is introduced?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We see no reason why it should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not be introduced on the basis that the developer can volunteer to provide an offset rather than go through the s.106 procedure.  If it were mandatory we can envisage developers who had already begun commissioning reports in anticipation of having to negot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iate a s.106 agreement being prejudiced. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 27: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you think an offsetting system should take a national approach to the question of significant harm and if so how? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As noted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> above, an obligation to asses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s significance creates uncertainty and expenditure. We would very much prefer the test to be based on thresholds. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 28: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you think any additional mechanisms need to be put in place to secure offsets beyond conservation covenants? If so why and w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">hat are they? If this includes measures not listed above, please explain what they are. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The developer is bound by a requirement to acquire an offset by the terms of the planning permission.  If the developer does not provide it personally it will do so o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n the basis of a contract with an offset provider. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In either instance there are sufficient enforcem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent mechanisms available. The pl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">anning authority can enforce ag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ainst the de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">veloper and the developer can take action und</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r the contract with the provider. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">suggest that for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">conservation covenant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to be an effective mechanism certain additional mechanisms should be put in place.  Firstly they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">able to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">regist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">red</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local land charge, and that from the date wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">en a conservation covenant is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">regis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tered it will be enforceable against successors in title to the original </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">covenantor.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Secondly, injunctions and contractual damages should be available to the beneficiary of the covenant in the event of the covenant being breached.  However</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he only circu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mstances in which we can see </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">exemplary damages </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">being legitimate is where the perpetrator has committed the act with a view to making a financial gain.  Exempl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ary damages could be ordered which would effectively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> confiscate it. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We do not believe these contractual remedies should be available to any third party, including the state.  It is a matter of a private agreement between the parties. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 29: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Do you think there should be constraints on what habitat can be provided as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> an offset? If so what constraints do you think should be put in place, and how should they work in practice? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We see no reason why this should not be a matter for the local planning authority to determine when determining the planning application. If it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">considers that an offset should require be similar to the destroyed habitat, it could so require, subject to conventional public law constraints. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 30: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you agree an offsetting system should apply a strategic approach to generate net ecological </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">gain in line with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Making Space for Nature</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">? If so, at what level should the strategy be set and who by? How should the system ensure compliance with the strategy? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">As discussed above in the context of the location of offsets, we see a place for this but it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> cannot be the sole approach.  We suggest it should be set at county level, although this need not mean that the offsets could only be provided within the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">count</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">y boundary. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">In the early stages</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">of the roll out of offsetting, a strategic approach could </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">create more obstacles than benefits.  The aspiration should be to ensure the system is functioning effectively and has the necessary “buy in” be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">fore deciding to regulate it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">by means of a strategic overview.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 31: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you think habitat banking should be allowed? Do you think a provider must show intent to create a habitat bank to be allowed to sell it as an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">offset? Do you think habitat banks should be “retired” if they are not used to provide an offset? If so, after </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">how long? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Yes it should and for the reasons given.  We suggest that an obligation to show intent is a prima facie an unnecessary imposition and this section of the consultation reads a little like it is trying to create obstacles. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The imperative should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be for the landowner </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to improve the biodiversity and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">environmental  management on his land. If he can subsequently sell as part of an offset providing business then that is all to the good. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 32: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you think maintaining an environmental gain that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic"> might otherwise be lost should count as an offset? If so, how should a value be attached to the offset? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Yes.  We suspect that with the decline in agri environment budgets, a number of sites that have hitherto benefited from public funding will be at ris</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">k of deteriorating.  Offsetting is one of the few ways of preventing that happening. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> 33: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you think it is acceptable or not to use biodiversity gain created for other purposes as an offset? If you do, how should it be decided what is allowed t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">o be used as an offset? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.25pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Yes. We suggest that anything which creates additionality should be included. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 34: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">How do you think the quality of assessments should be assured and who by? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">It should be a matter for the local planning authority.  The creation of some overarching body will simply result in additional bureaucracy for marginal, if any, gains. A system based on assessors will be even worse. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 35: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">ow should differences o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">f opinion over assessments be addressed? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Differences of opinion can be addressed via the planning system.  We do not see any issues that woul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">d fall outside its competence. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">There is no need to create a parallel structure. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 36: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">Do you think the m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">etric should take account of hedgerows? If so do you think the current approach is the right one or should it be adjusted? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">have no strong views on this and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">would not want the introduction </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">of an offsetting system to be delayed by concerns regarding the inclusion of hedgerows. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 37: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">o you think it should be possible to offset the loss of hedgerows by creating or restoring another form of habitat? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 38: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">If conservation covenants are put in place, do you think providing for offsetting through planning guidance will be sufficient to achieve national consistency? If not, what legislative provision may be necessary? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">We believe planning guidance should be su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">fficient. If it transpires that is not the case, further consideration can be given to the issue.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">17 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>